Humanitarian stakeholders from Nigeria and across the globe have emphasised the need to protect and empower internally displaced women and girls in Nigeria to be able to weather the challenges arising from the COVID-19 pandemic as the world celebrate World Humanitarian Day 2020. To commemorate the World Humanitarian Day 2020, Anneozeng Ogozi Aid Foundation (AOAF), a non-governmental organization, working tirelessly to provide support for vulnerable people, particularly children across 8 states in Nigeria, has partnered with other NGOs such as, The Wanda Audu Foundation and Mothers Rescue and Empowerment Initiative to provide food items, educational materials and toiletries for the children in Facado Orphanage home in Karu, Abuja. While appreciating aid workers for their selfless service, Anneozeng Ogozi Aid Foundation (AOAF) said, “For sacrificing their safety and comfort, risking the reality of getting killed and injured in the course of their work, yet despite the odds, aid workers continue to provide life-saving support and protection to people most in need.” AOAF will also be taking the children on hygiene sessions and sex education sessions in their bid to curb the rising cases of child sexual abuse. The Foundation has provided support to over 16 000 vulnerable children in less than two years of its existence. This year World Humanitarian Day comes as the world continues to fight the global COVID-19 pandemic. 